, "c": "Billy Strayhorn", "w": "38141"}]}, {"id": "18966", "date": "1948-11-13", "label": "Duke Ellington and His Orchestra", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["baritone_saxophone", "bass_clarinet"], "works": [{"t": "8 Humoresques, Op. 101: Humoresque (unspecified)", "c": "Antonín Dvorák", "w": "8715"}, {"t": "Cotton Tail", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "30186"}, {"t": "Paradise", "c": "Billy Strayhorn", "w": "25253"}, {"t": "Fantazm", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "38773"}]}, {"id": "20316", "date": "1964-03-29", "label": "Duke Ellington and His Orchestra", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["baritone_saxophone"], "works": [{"t": "Selections (unspecified)", "c": null, "w": "104450"}]}, {"id": "41777", "date": "1967-03-26", "label": "Jazz at the Philharmonic", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["alto_saxophone", "baritone_saxophone", "bass_clarinet", "clarinet"], "works": [{"t": "Rue Bleue", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67254"}, {"t": "Rockin' in Rhythm", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "59436"}, {"t": "Things Ain't What They Used To Be", "c": "Mercer Ellington", "w": "11294"}, {"t": "Cotton Tail", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "30186"}, {"t": "Selections (unspecified)", "c": null, "w": "104450"}, {"t": "Swamp Goo", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67252"}, {"t": "Girdle Hurdle", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67253"}, {"t": "Far East Suite: Mount Harissa", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67255"}, {"t": "Tutti for Cootie", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "106809"}, {"t": "Up Jump", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "117358"}, {"t": "Second Sacred Concert: The Shepherd (Who Watches Over the Night Flock)", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "36256"}, {"t": "Very Tenor", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67256"}]}, {"id": "19101", "date": "1967-03-26", "label": "Jazz at the Philharmonic", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["alto_saxophone", "baritone_saxophone", "bass_clarinet", "clarinet"], "works": [{"t": "Selections (unspecified)", "c": null, "w": "104450"}, {"t": "Salomé", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "117359"}, {"t": "A Chromatic Love Affair", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "117360"}, {"t": "Rue Bleue", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "67254"}, {"t": "Blood Count", "c": "Billy Strayhorn", "w": "33766"}]}, {"id": "18987", "date": "1968-04-04", "label": "Duke Ellington in His Concert of Sacred Music", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["baritone_saxophone"], "works": [{"t": "Second Sacred Concert: Praise God", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "36257"}]}], "works_created": [], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "Ray Drummond", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Harry Carney — his own sound. ... You hit a couple of notes — ooh, that’s Bill Evans. ... That was him. ... Anyone who is passionate about the music ... is instructive as to how I think the next level of jazz education needs to be", "doc_title": "Ray Drummond interviewed by Monk Rowe, Toronto, Canada, January 9, 2003", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/ray-drummond-interviewed-monk-rowe-toronto-canada-january-9-2003"}, {"speaker": "Nick Brignola", "relation": "friend of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "right until he died we were very good friends. I mean I used to go see that band every chance I could get to see them, and he always encouraged me", "doc_title": "Nick Brignola interviewed by Monk Rowe, Clinton, New York, July 28, 1997", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/nick-brignola-interviewed-monk-rowe-clinton-new-york-july-28-1997"}, {"speaker": "Ellis Marsalis", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "I asked this kid, I said, “Hey, man. Have you ever heard of a baritone saxophone player named Harry Carney?”", "doc_title": "Ellis Marsalis — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://americanhistory.si.edu/sites/default/files/file-uploader/Ellis-Marsalis-Transcription-2020.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Lawrence Brown", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Right. Uh-huh. ... We'd get to the next destination and then get out, check into a hotel, and maybe get to sleep, (but) probably not. You'd just change your clothes and go to the job. Harry Carney would have been driving all that time, and then he'd go play.", "doc_title": "52986_Lawrence Brown oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/52986/"}, {"speaker": "Louie Bellson", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Where were you going to get another player like Harry Carney, that baritone sound? ... I had to pinch myself many times. It got so intense that I said, am I really here? Yeah, there's Duke over there, playing piano.", "doc_title": "Louie Bellson — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Bellson-Louie/Bellson_Louie_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Charlie Barnet", "relation": "played with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "A picture of me sitting in the Ellington section with Johnny Hodges on one side and Harry Carney on the other... I wound up playing the whole set with Duke that night.", "doc_title": "52150_Charlie Barnet oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/52150/"}]}